Deep into RF bleachers With a 2-2 count Shawkey thought he threw strike three, but Ump Nallin called it ball three.  Yankee infielders all rushed the umpire to argue.  Mgr Huggins came out to prevent his players from saying anything too violent.  The game was delayed about five minutes by the squabble. Judge hit next pitch out.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

Harris jumped up and began to swap opinions with Scotty on the manner in which the ball had been applied to his anatomy. Both benches cleared to prevent them from fighting. W.Post claimed it was Scott who objected to Harris's slide.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

Browns argued it was foul and Ump Hildebrand agreed, but Ump Evans disallowed it and ordered Sisler and his men back into their positions.  Play resumed after several minutes' delay.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
Bush got a welcoming hand as he came to the plate1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

$Spectacular pickup of short bounder and threw him out with the same motion.  Dugan fell as he completed the throw and half-limped, half-staggered up and collapsed on the grass just outside the foul line.  His collapsible knee was thought to have gone bad on him.  He laid on the grass apparently unconscious as hundreds of fans liberated by the end of the game crowded about and were kept back with difficulty by the other players.  He was fanned and revived, then carried off the field on the shoulders of his mates.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
Beautiful 1-handed running catch robbed Ward of a triple1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

After Rice caught short fly, Combs ran a few feet down the line and stopped when Rice faked a throw.  Combs edged further along and Rice again feigned a toss.  When Combs was almost half way to the plate, he broke for home, causing the surprised Rice to make a bad throw to Severeid. Combs scored standing up.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
$Before the game a Peerless auto was driven to the Yankee dugout and presented to Bob Shawkey by his loving fans.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
Gehrig may have missed the squeeze signal1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

Ward lost short liner in sun but Paschal scooped it up and whipped it home. NYT reported Huggins gave orders to walk Schalk, but Ray 'reached over his head for Pennock's first pitch and dropped it into RF...Falk, as well as the Yankees, was taken by surprise and Paschal's good throw...cut him down by a close margin'. CDT: because Ray had knocked the cover off the ball in the 9th, Pennock decided to walk him.  The first pitch was wide and high.  Falk saw what was being done and turned back to 2B, but Schalk reached way out and poked it into RF.  Falk's poor jump proved costly.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
Falk fielded it and winged it home but Pennock slid safely.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

During batting practice Wally Pipp was struck above the right ear by a pitch thrown by Charlie Caldwell, rendering him unconscious.  He staggered for a few moments and fell. He was carried to the clubhouse and regained consciousness within a few minutes, but shortly after again became insensible.  He suffered from violent nausea but no bleeding (as was the case with Ray Chapman).  Pipp was taken to St. Vincent Hospital where he recovered quickly.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

$BOUNCE HR; hopped into the pavilion on the first bound. NYT: Slapped a high drive into LF close to the line.  Goslin and Scott raced toward it which looked as if it was going to drop into the foul territory of the open stand.  But it was fair by a couple of feet, bounded high off the sun-baked ground, and hopped into the stand. W.Post: Ordinary fly; Goslin misjudged it after a long run and had to let it drop, but it bounced sharply into the stands.  Lucky HR.1925NYA.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
